            "size": 1903,
            "text": "{\"model\":\"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001\",\"id\":\"msg_0193kzqANE68D9UgdKkSHTft\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Here are some fresh suggestions:\\n\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\\"keywords\\\": [\\n    \\\"meeting scheduler for remote teams\\\",\\n    \\\"calendar availability tool\\\",\\n    \\\"sync team schedules across zones\\\"\\n  ]\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThese keywords are effective for a scheduling tool because they:\\n\\n1. **Match User Intent** - They target people actively searching for solutions to scheduling problems, not just general interest. Someone searching \\\"meeting scheduler for remote teams\\\" is ready to solve a real pain point.\\n\\n2. **Reflect Your Solution** - They use language that mirrors how your product works (scheduler, sync, availability tool) rather than vague terms, which helps Google match your ads to the right audience.\\n\\n3. **Target Your Audience** - They include qualifiers like \\\"remote teams\\\" and \\\"across zones\\\" that speak directly to distributed companies—your ideal customers who understand the problem you solve.\\n\\n4. **Balance Specificity & Volume** - They're specific enough to attract qualified leads (not just anyone searching \\\"calendar\\\") but broad enough to capture variations of how people phrase their searches.\\n\\n5. **Avoid Rejected Patterns** - These new keywords steer clear of the phrases you rejected earlier (like \\\"eliminate scheduling back and forth\\\" or \\\"timezone meeting finder\\\") while still addressing the core scheduling challenge.\\n\\nThe best keywords connect searcher intent with your product's actual value—in this case, making distributed team scheduling effortless.\"}],\"stop_reason\":\"end_turn\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3682,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":0,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":0,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":0},\"output_tokens\":308,\"service_tier\":\"standard\"}}"
