        "response": {
          "bodySize": 2546,
          "content": {
            "mimeType": "application/json",
            "size": 2546,
            "text": "{\"model\":\"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001\",\"id\":\"msg_01GGNLuEb1g9WXztiuWHxvkP\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Great question! Let me break down why these keywords work well for your scheduling tool:\\n\\n## Why These Keywords Are Effective:\\n\\n**1. High Commercial Intent**\\n- Keywords like \\\"meeting scheduler for remote teams\\\" and \\\"timezone meeting coordinator\\\" show people are actively *looking for a solution* to their problem—not just researching. They're ready to buy or try.\\n- These match your target audience (remote teams, project managers) who are frustrated and searching for help *right now*.\\n\\n**2. Specific Problem-Solution Match**\\n- \\\"Remote team meeting scheduler\\\" directly addresses your audience's pain point (remote teams) + your solution (scheduling).\\n- \\\"Cross timezone scheduling tool\\\" captures the exact problem your product solves—the timezone coordination headache.\\n- This specificity means higher-quality clicks and better conversion rates than broad terms.\\n\\n**3. Natural Search Language**\\n- These phrases reflect how people actually talk about their problem in search bars, not marketing jargon.\\n- \\\"Global team calendar coordinator\\\" sounds like something someone would type when frustrated with scheduling, not a generic product category.\\n\\n**4. Alignment with Your Approved Keywords**\\n- The new keywords I suggested (\\\"remote team meeting scheduler,\\\" \\\"cross timezone scheduling tool,\\\" \\\"global team calendar coordinator\\\") follow the same pattern as your approved ones (\\\"meeting scheduler for remote teams,\\\" \\\"timezone meeting coordinator\\\").\\n- They use action-oriented language (scheduler, coordinator, tool) rather than passive terms like \\\"software\\\" or \\\"app.\\\"\\n\\n**5. Avoids Weak Patterns**\\n- The rejected keywords used vague terms like \\\"automatic,\\\" \\\"distributed,\\\" \\\"find,\\\" and \\\"availability\\\"—which are either too broad or don't clearly signal intent.\\n- Strong keywords are specific about *what* (scheduling) and *who* (remote/global teams), not just *how* (automatic/AI).\\n\\n**Bottom line:** These keywords connect your ads with people who have a specific problem, are actively searching for solutions, and match your exact offering. That's the recipe for high-performing ads.\"}],\"stop_reason\":\"end_turn\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3063,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":0,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":0,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":0},\"output_tokens\":443,\"service_tier\":\"standard\"}}"
