            "text": "{\"model\":\"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001\",\"id\":\"msg_01Vcx1L4WEwBqS7wWHcbH6nQ\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Great question! Let me break down what makes these keywords effective for your scheduling tool:\\n\\n**1. Search Intent Alignment**\\nThe best keywords match what your target audience is actively searching for. Your approved keywords like \\\"meeting scheduler for remote teams\\\" and \\\"automatic calendar coordination tool\\\" directly reflect the problem your solution solves. When someone searches these terms, they're already thinking about scheduling challenges—they're ready to consider a solution.\\n\\n**2. Specificity Over Breadth**\\nNotice how the keywords are specific phrases rather than single words like \\\"scheduler\\\" or \\\"calendar.\\\" This specificity is powerful because:\\n- It attracts people with clear intent (they know what they're looking for)\\n- It reduces wasted ad spend on irrelevant clicks\\n- It typically has lower competition, making your ads more cost-effective\\n\\n**3. Audience Recognition**\\nYour keywords use language your target audience actually uses. Phrases like \\\"remote teams,\\\" \\\"distributed teams,\\\" and \\\"calendar coordination\\\" speak directly to project managers and team leads dealing with multi-timezone challenges. They recognize themselves in these terms.\\n\\n**4. Commercial Intent**\\nThe best keywords for paid ads have transactional intent—people searching them are likely to convert. \\\"Meeting scheduler for remote teams\\\" signals someone actively looking for a tool, not just researching the concept.\\n\\n**5. Avoiding Rejected Patterns**\\nThe keywords I suggested avoid the rejected patterns because they:\\n- Don't focus on the *problem* alone (\\\"find meeting time across time zones\\\")\\n- Don't use generic software terminology (\\\"team scheduling software\\\")\\n- Don't emphasize pain points that might attract tire-kickers (\\\"eliminate scheduling back and forth\\\")\\n\\nInstead, they focus on the *solution* and the *audience*, which attracts higher-quality leads more likely to convert.\\n\\nDoes this help clarify the strategy? Would you like me to generate more keywords following this approach?\"}],\"stop_reason\":\"end_turn\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3046,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":0,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":0,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":0},\"output_tokens\":409,\"service_tier\":\"standard\"}}"
