            "mimeType": "application/json",
            "size": 2383,
            "text": "{\"model\":\"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001\",\"id\":\"msg_01TJ87XRp96oUySX7kneVZ2g\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Great question! Let me break down what makes these keywords effective for your scheduling tool:\\n\\n**1. Search Intent Alignment**\\nThe best keywords match what your target audience is actively searching for. Your approved keywords like \\\"meeting scheduler for remote teams\\\" and \\\"automatic calendar coordination tool\\\" work because they directly reflect the problem your solution solves. When someone searches these exact phrases, they're already thinking about scheduling tools—they're ready to buy.\\n\\n**2. Specificity Over Breadth**\\nNotice how the approved keywords are specific and descriptive (3-4 words) rather than generic single words like \\\"scheduler\\\" or \\\"calendar.\\\" This specificity means:\\n- Lower competition (cheaper clicks)\\n- Higher relevance (better quality score)\\n- More qualified leads (people actually looking for what you offer)\\n\\n**3. Audience Language**\\nYour keywords use the language your target audience uses. Remote teams and distributed companies think in terms of \\\"remote teams,\\\" \\\"distributed,\\\" and \\\"time zones.\\\" These phrases resonate because they speak directly to their pain point.\\n\\n**4. Commercial Intent**\\nThe strongest keywords have clear transactional intent. Words like \\\"scheduler,\\\" \\\"tool,\\\" and \\\"coordination\\\" signal someone is looking for a solution to implement—not just researching or learning about the topic.\\n\\n**5. Avoiding Rejected Patterns**\\nThe keywords you rejected (like \\\"find meeting time across time zones\\\" or \\\"eliminate scheduling conflicts\\\") were too focused on the problem rather than the solution. They're more informational than transactional, which means they attract people still exploring options rather than ready to convert.\\n\\nThe new keywords I suggested (\\\"distributed team meeting planner,\\\" \\\"calendar availability matcher,\\\" \\\"async scheduling for global teams\\\") follow this same logic—they're specific, solution-focused, and use language your audience actually searches for.\"}],\"stop_reason\":\"end_turn\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3032,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":0,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":0,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":0},\"output_tokens\":391,\"service_tier\":\"standard\"}}"
